\pard\f0\fs22 \b 13. Main Code Logic\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs22 \b 12.1 comments.py\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs22 DEFAULT_MODEL = os.getenv("ADK_MODEL", "gemini-2.5-flash")\par
\pard\f0\fs22 ORCHESTRATOR_AGENT_NAME = "voltstream_orchestrator_agent"\par
\pard\f0\fs22 ANALYST_AGENT_NAME = "voltstream_analyst_agent"\par
\pard\f0\fs22 ADVISOR_AGENT_NAME = "voltstream_advisor_agent"\par
\pard\f0\fs22 ENERGY_AGENT_LOOP = [...]\par
\pard\f0\fs22 comments.py keeps shared names, prompts, and loop text in one place. This keeps all agents consistent.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 \b 12.2 analyst_agent.py\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs22 def analyze_usage(message: str) -> dict[str, Any]:\par
\pard\f0\fs22 period = _usage_period(message)\par
\pard\f0\fs22 usage_history = get_usage_history(period)\par
\pard\f0\fs22 devices = get_devices()\par
\pard\f0\fs22 billing = get_billing_summary()\par
\pard\f0\fs22 return analysis\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Analyst Agent converts VoltStream usage and billing data into structured facts.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 \b 12.3 advisor_agent.py\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs22 def generate_recommendations(analysis: dict[str, Any]) -> dict[str, Any]:\par
\pard\f0\fs22 recommendations = []\par
\pard\f0\fs22 target_savings_kwh = round(total_grid_kwh * 0.12, 1)\par
\pard\f0\fs22 return \{"recommendations": recommendations, "target_savings_kwh": target_savings_kwh\}\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Advisor Agent converts the analysis into action-oriented recommendations.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 \b 12.4 orchestrator_agent.py\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs22 def _format_energy_answer(message, analysis, advice):\par
\pard\f0\fs22 lines = [grid_usage, solar_offset, net_usage]\par
\pard\f0\fs22 lines.extend(recommendations)\par
\pard\f0\fs22 return "\\n".join(lines)\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Orchestrator Agent controls routing and final response format.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 \b 12.5 runner_agent.py\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs22 def run_energy_usage_agent(message: str) -> dict[str, Any]:\par
\pard\f0\fs22 _orchestrator_agent_route(..., ANALYST_AGENT_NAME)\par
\pard\f0\fs22 analysis = analyze_usage(message)\par
\pard\f0\fs22 _orchestrator_agent_route(..., ADVISOR_AGENT_NAME)\par
\pard\f0\fs22 advice = generate_recommendations(analysis)\par
\pard\f0\fs22 answer = _format_energy_answer(message, analysis, advice)\par
\pard\f0\fs22 return \{"answer": answer, "tool_calls": trace, "agent_loop": ENERGY_AGENT_LOOP\}\par
\pard\f0\fs22 runner_agent.py executes the full Week 5 flow in the correct order.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 \b 14. Learning Objectives of Week 5 Task\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs22 The learning objectives of Week 5 focus on understanding how a backend agent system can grow from one agent into a coordinated multi-agent workflow. The main learning is how to separate analysis, advice, routing, and execution into different files while still returning one clean answer to the user.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Understand how multi-agent systems split work between specialist agents.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Understand the role of the Orchestrator Agent in routing, sequencing, and final answer formatting.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Understand the role of the Analyst Agent in reading usage history, solar offset, device loads, and billing data.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Understand the role of the Advisor Agent in creating practical recommendations and target savings.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Understand how comments.py centralizes model name, agent names, instructions, and the visible agent loop.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Understand how runner_agent.py executes the complete flow and records tool_calls.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Understand how FastAPI exposes the multi-agent workflow through /api/v1/agent.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Understand how tool_calls and ENERGY_AGENT_LOOP make the internal workflow explainable during demo.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 \b 15. Week 5 Topics Covered\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs22 The Week 5 task screenshot focuses on Agentic AI at the intermediate level. The important topics are not only the project files, but also the concepts behind deploying, invoking, tracing, and explaining an agent workflow. The topics below summarize the Week 5 learning points in simple project-related language.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 AgentCore\par
\pard\f0\fs22 AgentCore is the managed runtime concept from the Week 5 task. Compared with running an agent only on a local machine, AgentCore adds a cloud execution layer where the agent can be deployed, invoked, tracked, and managed. In documentation terms, it explains how the agent moves from local development toward a production-style runtime.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Strands Agent\par
\pard\f0\fs22 A Strands agent is the agent implementation style referenced in the Week 5 task. The main idea is to build an agent with clear tools, instructions, and a reasoning flow. In the VoltStream project, this maps to a multi-agent structure where the Orchestrator, Analyst, and Advisor each have focused responsibilities.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Sessions\par
\pard\f0\fs22 A session is used to keep track of an invocation context. The Week 5 screenshot asks to show the session ID and execution logs. This is important because a session ID proves that the request was not just a one-line response; it went through a tracked agent invocation flow.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Memory\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Memory means the ability to preserve useful context across agent interactions. In a production agent system, memory can help the assistant remember previous messages, user preferences, or task state. For VoltStream, memory could help continue an energy conversation across multiple prompts instead of treating every prompt as isolated.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Lifecycle management\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Lifecycle management refers to how an agent is packaged, started, invoked, monitored, updated, and stopped. This matters in Week 5 because deployment is more advanced than local execution. A deployed agent needs a stable runtime lifecycle so it can be called repeatedly and observed through logs.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Invocation through Lambda\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Invocation through Lambda means an external request can call a Lambda function, and Lambda can trigger the agent runtime. The screenshot specifically mentions the flow Lambda -> AgentCore -> Strands agent -> Bedrock -> response. This shows how an agent can be exposed through a cloud function instead of being manually run from a developer machine.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Execution logs\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Execution logs are records of what happened during an invocation. They help prove that the agent was called, which session was used, which route was followed, and whether the response was generated successfully. In the VoltStream documentation, tool_calls and ENERGY_AGENT_LOOP provide a local project-style trace of this same idea.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Two-agent system: Device Control Agent + Energy Advisor Agent\par
\pard\f0\fs22 The Week 5 task asks for a two-agent system idea: Device Control Agent plus Energy Advisor Agent. In the current VoltStream project, this is represented through specialist files. The device-control side handles device state, while the energy workflow uses Analyst and Advisor logic to understand usage and recommend savings actions.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 What AgentCore adds compared with local execution\par
\pard\f0\fs22 A managed runtime instead of only running Python locally.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Session IDs that help track invocations.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Execution logs for debugging and demonstration.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 Lifecycle management for deployment and repeated runtime use.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 A cloud invocation path through Lambda.\par
\pard\f0\fs22 A clearer route toward production deployment.\par
